step 1: Inserted the input files and executed reinsertion.py
step 2: manually correct the concordance and put it in 1-b-manually_corrected_conc/notes_formatted

step 3: segment the input files to find the passages that are likely to be mistaken. Todo: update the segmenter's lexicon (PyTib/data/…) Doing it will give better results when categorising, since only the real spelling mistakes will be marked as such.
step 4: automatically categorize the notes.
step 5: execute parse_json.py in 3-a-revition_format to create the files to DUCK.
step 6: bypass the DUCKing process and consider every note as K (keep it).

step 7: Insert the notes for every DUCKed file. output: - 0-1-formatted: keep the raw file in this folder (files kept there for reference) - 0-3-corrected: If you want to compare the output with other sources (Seraje Parkhang, Dharmadownload, …), open the files there and correct them. Use Meld for that purpose.

step 8: use 0-2_rawify.py to get a raw text file and a raw text file that keeps the "a"s from the initial .txt files
note: the script for step 7 is 0-1_apply_note_choices.py

step 8: With 1-1_unmark.py, create raw text files (unmarked) from the version from 0-3-corrected, to keep the modifications made during the eventual comparison with other sources. Then, with 1-2_segment_final.py, each text will have a file in 1-2-segmented where the remaining mistakes (or the ones added during comparison with other sources) are listed. A list of notes are proposed at the end of each file. If deemed necessary, apply any spelling corrections in the 1-3-post_seg folder. The tag to be inserted in the text is preceded by a couple of syllables so as to find the right place to insert it. The remainder of the line can then be added at the beginning of the notes. (The order of notes has no effect to the final rendition in Word).
step 10: copy the files from 1-3-post_seg to 2-1-a_reinserted so the line breaks can be reinserted during next step.

step 11: In prevision of reconstructing the Derge layout, reinsert the "a"s in the files using 2-1_reinsert_a.py
note: in step 10, use 1-3_copy_post_seg.py

step 12: reconstruct the Derge layout using 3-1_reinsert_page_nums.py
Here, check if all "a" were inserted correctly, looking at the beginning page in Derge and last page. The easiest is to go at the end of a Derge line and scroll down until the end of the file, so as to see lines with a double size. It shows that an "a" was missing there. Also look at the output in the console, as it will give indications of what went wrong for which file.
In order correct the "a"s: - modify the files in 2-0-with_a - rerun 2-1_reinsert_a.py (uses the Linux diff command, so must be executed in a Linux OS) - rerun 3-1_reinsert_page_nums.py - check if everything is ok.

step 11bis:
the files in 3-2-compared are copied by 3-1_reinserted_page_nums.py if they don't exist. So when the files in 2-0-with_a are modified, the corresponding files must be deleted from 3-2-compared

step 12: Remove the Derge layout while keeping the page tags using 3-3_copy_final.py. The files are directly copied from 3-2-compared. The files now reflect what would be in the Word file: the whole text in a single line with the derge page tags and notes.
step 14: Convert the final documents into Word files using layout.sh. Uses pandoc.
step 15: Once the Derge pages have been reconstructed (in 2-2-raw_page_reinserted), it is possible to generate layers using 5-layered-texts/generate_reinserted_editions.py
